The user has the opportunity to select how to structure the elements, either by models (bedroom 101, bedroom 102, …), by styles (modern, semi-modern, …) or by types of elements (wardrobe, bed, …).

# Adding and positioning elements

The adding and positioning of the elements starts from selecting the desired element from the menu and dragging it in the planning area where it will be positioned with the support of a snapping mechanism which allows for easier positioning next to other elements, be it walls, furniture or decoration.

## Selecting an element from the menu

When the user selects an element from the menu, all of the properties of the element are displayed in a block, when the element is dragged out of the menu the block shrinks to leave just the element at display which is done with an animation of the element, which is rotated from the angle, at which it is displayed in the menu to the angle at which it should be positioned in the planning area and the block shrinks using the ripple effect in reverse with the center being the element.

## Dropping an element in the planning area

When the user drops an element which is selected from the menu, the element in the menu is refreshed, it returns to its collapsed mode with little properties in display instead of the one with all the properties being displayed.

## Selecting an element from the planning area

When an element from the planning area is selected, buttons with all the options for manipulating the element pop out from beneath the element.

### Selection rectangle

When the user clicks somewhere in the planning area, a selection rectangle will start to be drawn with a starting point, corresponding to OnKeyDown (0) and an ending point, corresponding to OnKeyUp (0). This will select all elements the bounding boxes of which are completely selected (the bounding box is completely inside the selection rectangle) and correspond to the mode in which we are working in i.e. if we are in furniture mode, we will select only the elements which represent furniture and manipulate them together, they will move together, they will change texture together and they will resize together.

### Numerical guidance system

When we start manipulating an element, we will show numerical guidance i.e. if the user is moving an element, if the element is not snapped in the axis (there is some space between the closest element and the one which we are moving) we draw a line from the element&#39;s bounding box to the closest element&#39;s bounding box with a number representing the distance in cm in the middle of the line. Such lines are attempted to be drawn from all 8 sides of the bounding box of the element.

