### Selecting a &quot;furniture&quot; element

Selecting a furniture pops out the same options as the door and window elements:

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

1. The _color / texture change option_ opens a block for picking an element representing a color or a texture in a grid layout. Upon changing the texture, it asks if it should be applied to all other elements in the room, or maybe in the whole project (if there is only one room, the option for applying the color / texture to the whole project is redundant, therefore not shown).
2. The _move option_positions itself on top of the wall after it is revealed. When pressed, it enlarges itself and becomes transparent. When dragged, the wall follows the cursor. It leaves a shadow on the place where it will be positioned, which snaps to doors, walls and other furniture (all elements which are not from the category &quot;decoration&quot;).
3. The _resize option_ gives the opportunity to scale the furniture in 3 dimensions while keeping the thickness of the panels.
  - Upon changing the scale of the furniture, the scale of the texture is scaled in the opposite direction reciprocally. This provides for keeping the scale of the wooden texture according to real-world scale.
  - The panels keep have to keep their thickness. This is done by separating each panel and assigning a class to scale it. Each panel keeps its position relative to the furniture and its size in the appropriate axis with a pivot either in the center, its smallest point in the chosen axis or its greatest point in the chosen axis i.e. if the panel is horizontal, the options are bottom, middle and top.
4. The _remove option_ simply removes the element.
5. The _info_ displays a block containing descriptive information about the furniture like materials, dimensions, texture, price etc.

### Selecting a &quot;decoration&quot; element

Selecting a decoration gives only the opportunity to move it:

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

It as well follows the snapping principle and it snaps to everything.

Placing a decoration element on top of or inside a furniture element will make it its child object so that when the furniture moves, the decoration which completes its view will move with it.

## Snapping

The snapping mechanism represents a way to make it easier to place elements right next to other elements.

### Snapping to a grid

Note that when the user moves an element, the element snaps to round numbers, divisible by 5cm. This is valid for all elements, no matter the type or mode which they belong to.

Note that snapping to the grid is overridden by other snapping principles.

### Snapping to walls

If the element, which we are moving is translated to a position which is within proximity of a wall, it is being oriented so that it has the same orientation as the wall unless it has already been snapped to another wall already. If the user wants to place an element snapped to 2 perpendicular walls, they will most likely want the element to be with the orientation of the wall, it has been snapped to first. Upon changing the orientation which the element will have if the left mouse button is released, the &quot;shadow&quot; of this position linearly changes its rotation to match the one which is needed.

### Snapping to other elements

If the element, which we are moving is translated to a small proximity to another element (furniture snaps to other furniture and to &quot;room&quot; elements, as well as &quot;room&quot; elements, while decoration elements snap to everything else), the &quot;shadow&quot; will change its position to snap to the element&#39;s bounding box in order to indicate that the two elements will snap together.

## Position constrains

When positioning an element, we can see where it will be placed by the &quot;shadow&quot; of the position it will take after releasing the left mouse button and exiting the move mode. For this section only, &quot;element&quot; and &quot;furniture&quot; refer to those &quot;shadows&quot; of the elements and not the elements themselves. Using a shadow to show the position instead of the element itself will provide for keeping the responsibility while using the move option and showing the exact position of the element will take when released in real time which makes it possible for the user to get an idea about the constrains easily.

It is not possible to place two elements so that they overlap each other. Their bounding boxes cannot intersect with each other.

- There is a RigidBody on each element which gets activated upon entering the move option. This is done in order to be able to use the functionality of the colliders while making sure that we keep the positions of the other elements and so that we are able to easily constrain the position of the element.
- Upon moving an element, it checks if its Box Collider has collided with another element or not. If it has collided, the element will snap to it. This is achieved by placing a small trigger Box Collider next to the element which has the function of an area which upon triggering with activates the snapping and makes the element constrain its position to it on the appropriate axis. It is &quot;released&quot; from the snapping if and when the user tries to move the element further away from the snapping area so that it is not triggered with.

## Rotation constrains

The rotation of the elements is controlled by the snapping. When the element snaps to an element, it constrains its rotation on the appropriate axis. For example, if we want to place a furniture element rotated so that it is facing in the direction, at which the top wall is &quot;looking at&quot;, we have to snap the object to that wall first and say that we want to snap it to the right wall as well, we drag the element to the right until it reaches the snapping area of the right wall which constrains the position of the furniture on the last axis, but does not change its orientation because the furniture is already snapped to another element: the other wall.

Note that the floor does not count as an object to snap to but does count as a position constrainer. The orientation of all objects is fixed on the X and Z axis to 0 and can be rotated only along the Y axis, the vertical axis.

# 3D free-view mode

When the user enters the 3D free-view mode, they can select which room they want to work in. The one selected when switching to this mode is the one which covers the center of the visible planning area (if the menu is open, the center is different). There is a perspective camera which circles around the center of the room upon moving the mouse while pressing the middle button of the mouse. It can move backwards or forward when moving the mouse wheel with shifting the rotation of the camera so that the further away it is, the more downwards it is oriented to look at. If the camera collides with something or cannot see the center of the room if further away from it, the position of the camera is translated upwards. The user can manipulate the local rotation of the camera using the middle mouse button.

## Move mode

While in the 3D free-view mode, the pivot of the element follows the Raycast from the pointer on the screen and positions its &quot;shadow&quot; based on it. If the user wants to move only on one of the axis, this can be achieved through pressing the Shift key.

# 1st person view mode

The user enters the room from a 1st person view in order to explore it better and get a good &quot;sense&quot; of what their furniture will be like in their homes. There they can open and close doors and drawers. They can hear footsteps and so on. They can see the lighting in the rooms well. They can turn lights on and off, etc. There they can also manipulate elements there, be it moving them, changing the textures or resizing them.
## Interface

- **Navigation** is performed using the arrows or the letters A, W, S and D. The user can navigate through the rooms no matter what they are doing. This is useful while moving objects since the user can view the element they are manipulating from different angles without having to reactivate the move option again and again.
- **Jumping** is performed using the Space button. This provides the opportunity for the user to view the project from all positions they could view it from in real life.
- **Zooming in and out** is achieved through scrolling the mouse wheel.

## Clickable areas

A clickable area in 1st person view mode represents the case when the user hovers with the pointer over something they can interact with such as doors (be it doors to enter other rooms or doors on furniture) or drawers.
### Hover over

When the user hovers over a clickable area, it becomes highlighted and a text is displayed, a text which describes the action which will be performed upon clicking. For example, when the user hovers over a door, it is highlighted and the text &quot;open&quot; appears on the screen.

The text will be positioned on the place where the user would manipulate the object in order to perform the action i.e. the handle of the door or the drawer. If it is not visible from the current angle + position, it is displayed at the corner of the screen, which is closest to it. In other words, the text cannot go out of the screen:

 When the user points the 1st person camera at the button (when the button is at the center of the screen), then the options for manipulating the element appear which manipulate the whole element and not just the clickable part of it i.e. the door.
### Clicking

Clicking anywhere in the clickable area will make it perform its action unless the user has hovered over the button with the text which describes the action i.e. &quot;open&quot;, has revealed the other options and has clicked on any of them. In other words, the buttons for the other options for manipulating the element overrides the execution of the action, which should be performed upon clicking in the clickable area i.e. opening the door.

### Types of clickable elements

Clickable areas represent area where clicking an area triggers an action to be performed, but those actions can be of different types, along with that, there are 1 st person specific elements such as lamps and lamp keys which the user can activate only when in 1st person mode and those types are:
#### Lamp key

The action, which is triggered upon clicking a lamp key is to activate or deactivate the lamp which is associated with it. Such lamps reside in the ceilings of the rooms and can be manipulated as well. Options for manipulating a lamp key are:

1. 1)The _trigger option_ triggers the lamp, associated with the particular lamp key on and off.
2. 2)The _color change option_ opens a block for picking from a set of colors, presented in a grid layout.
3. 3)The _intensity change option_ reveals a slider for changing the intensity of the light, which has a step of 0.1 and ranges from 0 to 2.
4. 4)The _move option_enlarges itself and becomes transparent upon clicking. When dragged, the key follows the cursor. It leaves a shadow on the place where it will be positioned, which snaps to walls.
5. 5)The _remove option_ simply removes the element.

#### Lamp

